MP Theodore ending space proof;<br> Given $\tan(z)=a$, we have $\sin(z)=ka$ and $\cos(z)=k$ where $k^2+a^2=1$. Now taking the conjugate we have $\sin(\bar{z})=\bar{k}a$ and $\cos(\bar{z})=\bar{k}$. Hence we have $\overline{\sin(z)\cos(z)+i\tan(z)}=\overline{(ka)\cdot k+i\cdot a}=k^2a-ia=k\cdot \bar{z}+i\bar{z}=\sin(\bar{z})\cos(\bar{z})+i\tan(\bar{z})$. But by noting $\cos(z)=-\cos(\bar{z})$, we get $\sin(z)\cos(z)+i\tan(z)=-\sin(\bar{z})\cos(\bar{z})+i\tan(\bar{z})$. Hence the real value is $\sin(z)\cos(z)+i\tan(z)=ka^2+ik\sqrt{1-k^2}$. Taking real and imaginary parts we have $(ka)^2+(ik\sqrt{1-k^2})^2=k^2a^2-k^2\sqrt{1-k^2}^2=0$</ think> ARGA Solution </ think>B <answer>$i \sin 2x$</answer>

